@page "/counter-wasm"
@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly

@*
    Counter Page - Interactive WebAssembly Rendering

    KEY CONCEPTS:
    - @rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly means UI interactions are processed in the BROWSER
    - .NET runtime runs in browser via WebAssembly (downloaded on first visit)
    - User clicks button -> WASM processes event locally -> state updates -> UI re-renders
    - State lives in browser memory, persisted to LocalStorage
    - Good for: offline-capable apps, reduced server load, fastest interactions
    - Tradeoff: larger initial download (~2MB), limited server access

    WHY THIS FILE IS IN THE CLIENT PROJECT:
    Components using InteractiveWebAssembly or InteractiveAuto MUST be in the
    .Client project because they need to be compiled to WebAssembly.
    The Server project references the Client project and serves these components.

    BUSTAND WORKS THE SAME:
    - Same ZustandComponent inheritance pattern
    - Same UseState() subscription pattern
    - Same Store.Method() calls
    - Bustand is rendering-mode agnostic!

    STORE LOCATION:
    CounterStore is also in this Client project (Bustand.Sample.Client.Stores).
    This is intentional - stores must be in Client for WASM/Auto components to use them.
*@

@inherits ZustandComponent<CounterStore, CounterState>

<PageTitle>Counter (WebAssembly)</PageTitle>

<h1>Counter (WebAssembly)</h1>

<p class="render-mode-info">
    <strong>Render Mode:</strong> Interactive WebAssembly
    <br />
    <small>State changes are processed in the browser via .NET WASM runtime.</small>
</p>

<div class="counter-display">
    <p>Current count: <strong>@count</strong></p>
</div>

<div class="counter-buttons">
    <button class="btn btn-primary" @onclick="Store.Increment">
        Increment
    </button>

    <button class="btn btn-secondary" @onclick="Store.Decrement">
        Decrement
    </button>

    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary" @onclick="Store.Reset">
        Reset
    </button>
</div>

<div class="counter-custom">
    <h4>Increment by custom amount:</h4>
    <input type="number" @bind="customAmount" min="1" />
    <button class="btn btn-info" @onclick="() => Store.IncrementBy(customAmount)">
        Add @customAmount
    </button>
</div>

<div class="explanation">
    <h4>How it works:</h4>
    <ol>
        <li>This page uses <code>@("@")rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly</code></li>
        <li>On first visit, .NET runtime + app DLLs are downloaded (~2MB)</li>
        <li>Subsequent visits use cached runtime (fast startup)</li>
        <li>The CounterStore runs entirely in the browser</li>
        <li>Button clicks are handled locally - no server round-trip!</li>
        <li>Persistence writes directly to browser's LocalStorage</li>
    </ol>
    <p><em>Try it offline - it works without a server connection!</em></p>
</div>

@code {
    // Subscribe to the Count slice of state
    // UseStateResult<int> has implicit conversion to int, so we can use @count in markup
    private UseStateResult<int> count;
    private int customAmount = 5;

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        // UseState subscribes to state changes and triggers re-render automatically
        count = UseState(state => state.Count);
    }
}
